# Agent Orchestrator Protocol

This is the tool-agnostic operating protocol for coordinating Codex, Claude Code, and other terminal-based coding agents.

Use this protocol whenever an agent acts as the architect/controller for parallel software work. The orchestrator coordinates work; it does not implement feature code unless explicitly asked.

## Source Of Truth

The mission folder is the execution source of truth:

```text
.agents/orchestration/<mission>/
  mission.md
  backlog.md
  daily-sprint.md
  goal.md
  acceptance.md
  verification.md
  linear-sync.md
  contract.md
  ownership.md
  ownership.yaml
  board.md
  integration-plan.md
  decision-log.md
  runlog.md
  incidents.md
  lessons.md
  runtime.json
  handoff.md
  tasks/
  reports/
  logs/
  locks/
```

Linear is the external project board. The mission folder remains the technical record.

## Orchestrator Role

The orchestrator must:

1. Translate business tasks, bugs, and ideas into a mission, daily sprint, waves, and agent task briefs.
2. Define a verifiable stop condition in `goal.md`, pass/fail criteria in `acceptance.md`, and checks in `verification.md`.
3. Create/update Linear projects, issues, subissues, comments, and status sync when tools are available.
4. Freeze `contract.md` and `ownership.md` before launching parallel editing workers.
5. Assign one branch and one worktree per editing worker.
6. Launch or instruct launch of workers using approval-minimized commands.
7. Review reports, update the board, sync Linear, and plan the next wave.
8. Escalate only consolidated decisions to the user.
9. Keep context in files and generate `handoff.md` after waves and at end of day.
10. Record operational failures in `incidents.md` and promote reusable fixes to `lessons.md`.

The orchestrator must not:

- Let workers change shared contracts ad hoc.
- Let workers push, merge, deploy, or run destructive git commands unless explicitly approved.
- Mark work done before integration and verification.
- Hide blockers or unresolved contract mismatches.

## Agent Selection

Use `AGENT_SELECTION.md` as the default role policy.

Default division of labor:

- Claude Code is the default implementation worker for scoped code changes.
- Claude Code is also the default broad investigator for logs, CI, and incident evidence.
- Codex is the default orchestrator, reviewer, integrator, and verifier.
- Workers recommend Linear changes in reports; the Codex orchestrator performs Linear sync.

This separation is intentional: implementation output should be reviewed by a separate controller before integration or acceptance.

## Daily Flow

1. Intake
   - Capture business goals, spontaneous bugs, ideas, and small fixes in `backlog.md`.
   - Classify each item by type, priority, risk, area, dependencies, and acceptance criteria.

2. Sprint Planning
   - Pick one clear daily mission.
   - Define done criteria and verification gates in `daily-sprint.md`.
   - Write `goal.md` with business outcome and done state.
   - Write `acceptance.md` with concrete pass/fail criteria.
   - Write `verification.md` with local and semantic checks.
   - Create or update the Linear project/parent issue and task issues.

3. Contract And Ownership
   - Write `contract.md` before parallel backend/frontend/DB work.
   - Write `ownership.md` with disjoint write scopes.
   - Write `ownership.yaml` for machine-checkable path rules.
   - Sequence tasks that need the same files or shared migrations.

4. Wave Execution
   - Write one task brief per worker in `tasks/`.
   - Launch workers with a clear report path in `reports/`.
   - Append starts/results to `runlog.md`.
   - Workers ask no direct user questions; they stop and report blockers.

5. Report Review
   - Read reports.
   - Compare files changed against `ownership.md`.
   - Check requested contract changes.
   - Sync board and Linear status.
   - Decide next wave, integration, blocker resolution, or backlog.
   - Evaluate progress against `goal.md`.
   - Check acceptance criteria and verification evidence.
   - Record avoidable failures or repeated friction in `incidents.md`.
   - Promote reusable rules to `lessons.md` and update protocol/templates/scripts when appropriate.

6. Integration
   - Use one integrator.
   - Merge branches in `integration-plan.md` order.
   - Run focused checks after each merge and full verification at the end.
   - Record durable business/architecture decisions in `decision-log.md`.

7. Handoff
   - Generate `handoff.md`.
   - Use it to resume in Codex or Claude Code without relying on chat history.
   - Include incidents and accepted lessons in the handoff.
   - Include goal status and missing evidence.

## Goal Evaluation Loop

Use `GOAL_EVALUATION.md` for the detailed procedure.

The durable goal lives in `goal.md`. Native `/goal` features may be used when available, but they do not replace mission-level goal state.

Required loop:

```text
define goal.md
  -> define acceptance.md and verification.md
  -> launch scoped workers
  -> collect reports/evidence
  -> evaluator checks goal.md and acceptance.md
  -> complete OR not complete
  -> if not complete, launch only the smallest next wave needed for missing evidence
```

The evaluator returns only:

- `complete`
- `not complete`

If not complete, it must list the smallest missing evidence or blocker.

## Self-Improvement Loop

Use `SELF_IMPROVEMENT.md` for the detailed procedure.

The required loop is:

```text
failure or repeated friction
  -> record incident in incidents.md
  -> identify root cause
  -> apply immediate fix
  -> promote reusable lesson to lessons.md
  -> update the smallest durable surface that prevents recurrence
  -> include the lesson in handoff.md
```

Durable surfaces include:

- shared protocol files;
- task/report templates;
- worker type templates;
- launch/status/handoff scripts;
- mission scaffold defaults;
- project-local `CLAUDE.md` and `AGENTS.md` when the rule is area-specific.

Do not treat every one-off failure as a new global rule. Lessons must be specific, reusable, and testable.

## Approval Policy

Pre-approved inside an approved wave:

- Read repository files.
- Edit only assigned write scopes.
- Run focused tests and static checks.
- Start local dev servers on assigned ports.
- Write reports.

Always requires user approval:

- Commit, unless explicitly allowed for the wave.
- Push.
- Merge to integration, main, release, or production branches.
- Staging or production deploy.
- `.env*`, secrets, deploy scripts, GitHub Actions deploy workflow, Cloud Run services/jobs.
- Destructive git commands.
- Shipped Alembic revision edits.
- Architecture invariant changes.
- PHI-sensitive decisions.

## Intake Decisions

Every new bug, idea, or small fix must go through the orchestrator:

```text
do now
do next wave
do after integration
put in backlog
stop current work
ask user approval
```

Workers must not absorb new scope informally.

## Tool Adapters

Codex:

- Use `.agents/skills/agent-orchestrator/SKILL.md`.
- Prefer `codex exec` workers with `--sandbox workspace-write --ask-for-approval never`.

Claude Code:

- Use `.claude/commands/orchestrator.md`.
- Prefer `claude --permission-mode dontAsk` workers with high-risk commands disallowed.

Both adapters must follow this protocol and use the same mission folder.

