# Approval Policy

The goal is to approve bounded waves, not every command.

## Pre-Approved Inside A Wave

Workers may:

- read repository files;
- edit assigned write scopes only;
- run focused tests and checks;
- start local dev servers on assigned ports;
- write reports;
- propose follow-up tasks.
- run read-only GitHub Actions, GitHub PR, Cloud Logging, and Cloud Run
  inspection commands when the task brief assigns diagnostics work.
- run local formatting, linting, typechecking, pytest targets, YAML
  parsing, and focused helper scripts needed to validate their assigned
  scope.

## Stop And Report

Workers must stop and report to the orchestrator if:

- they need files outside the allowed write scope;
- the shared contract is wrong or incomplete;
- another worker conflicts with their files;
- tests fail for unclear reasons;
- migration, env, deployment, secret, dependency, or GitHub Actions changes become necessary;
- branch switching, merge, rebase, push, deploy, or destructive git commands become necessary.

## User Approval Required

- Commit unless explicitly allowed.
- Push.
- Merge to integration/main/release branches.
- Staging or production deploy.
- GitHub Actions workflow dispatch, rerun, cancel, approval, or any
  operation that changes workflow state.
- Cloud Run service/job update, deploy, delete, traffic change, env var
  change, secret binding change, or IAM policy change.
- Destructive git commands.
- `.env*`, secrets, deploy scripts, GitHub Actions deploy workflow, Cloud Run services/jobs.
- Shipped Alembic revision edits.
- Architecture invariant changes.
- PHI-sensitive decisions.

## Recommended Worker Modes

Use broad-enough permissions to avoid blocking normal bounded work. The
primary safety mechanism is the task brief plus Codex review of:

- command history summarized in the report;
- changed files against `ownership.md`;
- focused tests and verification results;
- no push/merge/deploy/traffic mutation unless explicitly approved.

Codex:

```bash
codex --sandbox workspace-write --ask-for-approval never exec --cd <worktree> "<prompt>"
```

Claude Code:

```bash
claude --permission-mode dontAsk \
  --disallowedTools "Bash(git push*) Bash(git reset*) Bash(git clean*) Bash(git merge*) Bash(git rebase*) Bash(gh workflow run*) Bash(gh run rerun*) Bash(gh run cancel*) Bash(gcloud run services update*) Bash(gcloud run services replace*) Bash(gcloud run services delete*) Bash(gcloud run services update-traffic*) Bash(gcloud run deploy*) Bash(gcloud run jobs update*) Bash(gcloud run jobs execute*) Bash(gcloud iam*) Bash(gcloud secrets*) Bash(*terraform*) Bash(*rm -rf*)" \
  --add-dir <worktree> \
  "<prompt>"
```

Do not use full bypass modes for normal workers.

## Recommended Claude Allowlist

The project or local Claude settings should allow these common bounded
commands so agents do not stall on normal implementation and diagnostic
work:

Local implementation and verification:

- `Bash(python -m pytest*)`
- `Bash(python3 -m pytest*)`
- `Bash(.venv/bin/python -m pytest*)`
- `Bash(python -m mypy*)`
- `Bash(python3 -m mypy*)`
- `Bash(.venv/bin/python -m mypy*)`
- `Bash(python -m ruff*)`
- `Bash(python3 -m ruff*)`
- `Bash(.venv/bin/python -m ruff*)`
- `Bash(make lint*)`
- `Bash(make test*)`
- `Bash(make verify*)`
- `Bash(make verify-deploy*)`
- `Bash(python -c*)`
- `Bash(python3 -c*)`

GitHub read and PR diagnostics:

- `Bash(gh auth*)`
- `Bash(gh pr*)`
- `Bash(gh run list*)`
- `Bash(gh run view*)`
- `Bash(gh api /repos/*/actions*)`
- `Bash(gh api repos/*/actions*)`

Google Cloud read-only diagnostics:

- `Bash(gcloud auth*)`
- `Bash(gcloud config*)`
- `Bash(gcloud logging read*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run services list*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run services describe*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run revisions list*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run revisions describe*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run jobs list*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run jobs describe*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run jobs executions list*)`
- `Bash(gcloud run jobs executions describe*)`
- `Bash(gcloud monitoring*)`

Still avoid broad permissions like `Bash(gcloud run*)`,
`Bash(gh api*)`, `Bash(git push*)`, or `Bash(git merge*)` for unattended
workers. If a task genuinely needs one of those, it is a gated operator
task, not a normal worker task.

