# Linear Sync Protocol

Linear is the external project board. The mission folder is the technical source of truth.

## Ownership

Only the orchestrator creates, splits, moves, reprioritizes, comments on, or closes Linear issues unless a dedicated Linear-admin task says otherwise.

Workers may:

- reference their assigned Linear issue;
- recommend status changes in reports;
- suggest new issues in reports.

Workers must not:

- create new Linear issues;
- change issue statuses;
- close issues;
- change priority;
- split or reparent issues.

## Status Mapping

Default mapping:

| Orchestration Status | Linear Status |
| --- | --- |
| intake | Backlog |
| planned | Ready |
| running | In Progress |
| blocked | Blocked |
| needs-integration | Needs Integration |
| reviewing | In Review |
| verified | Verified |
| done | Done |

Confirm actual team status names with Linear before syncing.

## Issue Decomposition

Business task -> Linear project or parent issue.

Mission waves -> child issues/subissues:

- backend/API;
- frontend/UI;
- DB/migration;
- tests/verification;
- docs/handoff;
- integration;
- release gate.

## Sync Events

- New mission: create/update project and parent issue.
- New wave: create/update task issues.
- Worker starts: move to In Progress.
- Worker blocked: move to Blocked and comment the blocker.
- Worker complete: move to Needs Integration unless read-only.
- Integration started: move integration issue to In Progress.
- Integration complete: move affected issues to In Review.
- Full verification pass: move to Verified.
- Release/defer accepted: move to Done.

## Fallback

If Linear tools are unavailable, update `linear-sync.md` with intended changes and mark them pending.

